iness, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-08","Offshore Renewable Energy Catapult","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many full-time equivalent staff are employed in the Offshore Renewable Energy Catapult; where those employees are based and how much funding the Catapult has allocated to each NUTS 1 region.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","121479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818716","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-16","<p>The Rutherford Fund will invest more than £100m from 2017/18 to 2020/21, to attract world-leading research talent to the UK, mostly through fellowships at UK universities. The Fund is delivered through partners including the four National Academies, the British Council, Research Councils (and UKRI from April 2018), and others. The Fund makes individual appointments based principally on the quality of research. Government has not set any requirement for delivery partners to allocate funding on a regional or NUTS 1 basis.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-01-16T15:15:10.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818716/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818716/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818716/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-08","Rutherford Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much money the Rutherford Fund has allocated to each NUTS 1 region in each year since its creation.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","121480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818717","Department for Education","false","2018-01-16","<p>The competition to establish new Institutes of Technology (IoT) opened on 15 December 2017 and the deadline for proposals is 1 March 2018. Following assessment of the proposals we expect to announce those that are successful by the end of this year. We expect the first IoTs to be established from September 2019.</p><p> </p><p>The detailed competition timetable is below. Further information for applicants is available on the GOV.UK website.</p><p> </p><p>Competition Timetable</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Date</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Activity</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>15 December 2017</p></td><td><p>Call for proposals opens</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>16 January 2018</p></td><td><p>IoT Conference for applicants</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1 March 2018</p></td><td><p>Deadline for submission of proposals</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Early May 2018</p></td><td><p>Notification of outcome of Stage One</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>June 2018</p></td><td><p>Stage Two competition launched</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Summer 2018</p></td><td><p>Stage Two business plans submitted</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>By end 2018</p></td><td><p>Announcement of successful proposals</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September 2019</p></td><td><p>First IoTs established</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31 March 2021</p></td><td><p>Capital fund spend deadline</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2018-01-16T17:42:11.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818717/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818717/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818717/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-08","Institutes of Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the timetable is for the establishment of the new Institutes of Technology.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","121481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818718","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-11","<p>A large proportion of funding from the NPIF – established at Autumn Statement 2016 and expanded to £31bn at Autumn Budget 2017 – has already been allocated to its four target sectors: transport, housing, digital communications and R&amp;D. Breakdowns within these sectors can be found on page 44 of the 2017 Autumn Budget document. Specific projects are selected through a variety of mechanisms that are tailored to achieve programme goals and ensure high value for money.</p><p> </p><p>Funding allocations from the NPIF are not specifically made by region. However the NPIF is intended to fund projects that help to boost productivity and prosperity throughout the UK and across regions. For example, at the Autumn Budget 2017, the government made an allocation specifically benefitting the North East, announcing £337m of new funding from the NPIF to replace rolling stock on the Tyne &amp; Wear Metro. It also established a new £1.7bn Transforming Cities Fund. This funding will be widely distributed, with £840m of per capita funding to be transferred to the six Mayoral Combined Authorities with directly elected mayors, and £840m open for competition for transport projects in cities. These announcements and others demonstrate a commitment to invest to improve productivity in all UK regions.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-01-11T14:16:03.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818718/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818718/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818718/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-08","National Productivity Investment Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to page 130 of the Industrial Strategy, published in November 2017, how much has funding has been allocated to (a) transport, (b) housing, (c) digital and (d) research & development in each NUTS 1 region by the National Productivity Investment Fund.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","121482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818719","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-16","<p>The Government’s ambitious, modern Industrial Strategy sets out a long term plan to boost the productivity and earning power of people throughout the UK. We are committed to providing high quality infrastructure to support economic growth and prosperity across all regions of the country, and our approach to major investments will reflect this. While cost-benefit analysis will remain central to our decision-making, we will also make use of broad-based and dynamic assessment techniques that reflect the full potential for infrastructure to support local economies.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-01-16T11:54:19.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818719/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818719/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818719/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-08","Regional Planning and Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, with reference to page 132 of the Industrial Strategy, published in November 2017, what the process will be for the Government to take greater account of disparities between productivity and economic opportunity between different places when making future investment decisions.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","121483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818720","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-16","<p>The Government is investing £2.6 billion (including the additional £76m announced in the last Budgert) between 2015 and 2021, delivering at least 1,500 new flood defence schemes and better protecting 300,000 homes. The six year Capital Investment Programme will provide Flood Defence Grant-in-Aid as shown below for flood and coastal risk management schemes by NUTS 1 regions.</p><p> </p><p>Where appropriate, property level flood protection measures are integrated within flood risk management schemes. The Government does not hold information centrally about the breakdown of spending for individual elements, such as property level protection measures, of these schemes.</p><p> </p><p>The nationally coordinated project investment includes flood defences which are located in more than one NUTS 1 region, and capitalised costs which support the development of these physical and natural defences.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>NUTS1 region</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>NUTS1 code</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total government planned capital expenditure (£m) between April 2015 and March 2021 </strong>(Excluding £76m FROM LAST BUDGET)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>East Midlands</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>UKF</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>198</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>East of England</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>UKH</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>217</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Greater London</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>UKI</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>134</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>North East </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>UKC</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>46</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>North West </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>UKD</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>210</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>South East </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>UKJ</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>510</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>South West </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>UKK</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>176</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>West Midlands </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>UKG</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>75</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Yorkshire and The Humber</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>UKE</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>487</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>NATONALLY COORDINATED PROJECT INVESTMENT</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>452</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-01-16T17:26:38.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818720/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818720/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818720/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-08","Flood Control: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural affairs, with reference to page 135 of the Industrial Strategy, published in November 2017, how much funding has been allocated from the public purse to (a) flood defence schemes and (b) household flood protection in each NUTS 1 region.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","121484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818721","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-16","<p>Page 156 of the industrial strategy refers to a market response case study on a partnership between Vodafone and CityFibre. As this is a market response rather than a Government initiative we do not hold the details of their commercial strategy regarding the roll-out of full fibre.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-01-16T14:27:16.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818721/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818721/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818721/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-08","Broadband: Urban Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to page 156 of the Industrial Strategy, published in November 2017, which towns and cities which will benefit from the roll-out of full fibre in 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","121485"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818722","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-15","<p>The Cultural Development Fund will use £2 million funding for 2018/19 to test the model for place-based cultural development and support towns and cities to develop culture and creative industries led growth strategies. No decisions have yet been made on which regions will benefit from funding.</p>","Northampton North","Michael Ellis",,"2018-01-15T15:01:12.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818722/answer","Biography information for Michael Ellis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818722/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818722/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-08","Culture: Urban Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to page 234 of the Industrial Strategy, published in November 2017, to which cities will the £2 million in place-based cultural development be allocated.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","121486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818723","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-16","<p>On 23<sup>rd</sup> December 2017 the Department launched a consultation on ‘Proposals for the creation of a Major Road Network’. This consultation will close on 19<sup>th</sup> March 2018.</p><p> </p><p>A formal consultation response will be published during summer 2018 prior to the launch of the Major Road Network (MRN) programme before the end of the year.</p><p> </p><p>The MRN will receive a dedicated portion of the National Roads Fund which will be established in 2020/21.</p><p> </p><p>The Department will consider whether there is a need to identify schemes for early entry to the MRN Investment Programme.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-01-16T11:04:17.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818723/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818723/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818723/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-08","Roads: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the timetable is for the introduction of new funding for the major road network.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","121487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818724","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-16","<p>More than 3000 permanent jobs will be created through the operation and maintenance of HS2. For Phase One of the project they will be located in the NUTS1 regions of West Midlands, London and the South East, since this is where Phase One will operate. The locations for Phase 2 are not available at this stage.</p><p> </p><p>The Scheme will also support growth in the wider economy worth an additional 100,000 jobs, with the majority of jobs created being outside London.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-01-16T11:26:16.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818724/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818724/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818724/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-08","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to page 140 of the Industrial Strategy, published in November 2017, in which NUTS 1 regions will the 3,000 permanent HS2 jobs be based.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","121488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818725","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-16","<p>The timetable for the deployment of this infrastructure is in the early stages of development, and we will announce further details in due course.</p><p> </p><p>The Trans Pennine Initiative will deliver infrastructure that enables the testing and delivery of rail passenger connectivity on an existing rail route and the viability of using the rail corridor to deploy high capacity, cost effective fibre. A longer route would cost more and, crucially, would take longer to build. These trials are a step on the way to improving rail passenger communications on all mainline routes by 2025.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-01-16T14:29:21.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818725/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818725/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818725/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-08","Railways: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to page 153 of the Industrial Strategy, published in November 2017, what the timetable is for the installation of trackside infrastructure along the Trans-Pennine Route between Manchester, Leeds and York and for what reasons the plans not extend to Hull.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","121489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818726","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-16","<p>The Housing Infrastructure Fund launched on 4 July 2017 will unlock up to 100,000 new homes by supporting the delivery of vital physical infrastructure projects such as roads, bridges, energy networks and other utilities. We are currently assessing proposals in partnership with all key stakeholders and will announce successful schemes over the coming months.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-01-16T10:46:02.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818726/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818726/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818726/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2018-01-08","Housing Infrastructure Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how much funding has been allocated from the Housing Infrastructure Fund to each NUTS 1 region in each year since that fund's creation.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","121490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818727","Department for Education","false","2018-01-16","<p>Being fluent in reading is vital for young children’s future success. The results of the 2016 Progress in International Reading Study, announced in December 2017 showed that our nine year olds in England had achieved the highest ever scores. This puts the Department’s continued success in phonics and raising education standards on a global scale. This year, thanks to Government reforms and the hard work of teachers across the country, 154,000 more six year olds are on track to be fluent in reading in 2012.</p><p> </p><p>The Department wants to build on these successes and support improvements in areas where standards are lower than average. The Department has announced that we will set up a new Centre of Excellence for Literacy Teaching and a national network of 35 English Hubs across the country. The exact locations of hubs will be decided in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-01-16T16:11:47.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818727/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818727/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818727/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-08","English Language: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to page 113 of the Industrial Strategy, published in November 2017, in which locations her Department plans to establish the network of English hubs.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","121491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818728","Department for Education","false","2018-01-16","<p>There is currently a network of 35 mathematics hubs. These are located in the following NUTS 1 regions:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>NUTS 1 region</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of mathematics hubs</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East Midlands</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East of England</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North East</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North West</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South East</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South West</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>West Midlands</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Yorkshire and the Humber</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>As outlined in the Industrial Strategy, we will announce new mathematics hubs in under-achieving areas later this year.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-01-16T17:28:20Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818728/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818728/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818728/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-08","Mathematics: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to page 112 of the Industrial Strategy, published in November 2017, how many Maths hubs have been set up in each NUTS 1 region and in which under-achieving areas she plans to establish the new Maths hubs.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","121492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818729","Department for Education","false","2018-01-16","<p>The Department is developing delivery options for the Teacher Development Premium and will announce full details in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-01-16T17:47:24.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818729/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818729/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818729/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-08","Teachers: Career Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to paragraph 5.8 of Autumn Budget 2017, in which area will the Teacher Development Premium will be piloted.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","121493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818730","Department for Education","false","2018-01-16","<p>The Teaching for Mastery programme has been rolled out to 2,671 schools across England. These are located in the following NUTS 1 regions:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>NUTS 1 region</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of Teaching for Mastery schools</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Proportion of Teaching for Mastery schools (%)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East Midlands</p></td><td><p>272</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East of England</p></td><td><p>257</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London</p></td><td><p>416</p></td><td><p>16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North East</p></td><td><p>142</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North West</p></td><td><p>329</p></td><td><p>12</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South East</p></td><td><p>418</p></td><td><p>16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South West</p></td><td><p>270</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>West Midlands</p></td><td><p>248</p></td><td><p>9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Yorkshire and the Humber</p></td><td><p>319</p></td><td><p>12</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The Department is committed to the programme reaching half of all primary schools by 2020. Estimates of take-up by region by 2020 are not available.</p><p> </p><p>As outlined in the Industrial Strategy, we will be announcing additional maths hub capacity in under-achieving areas later this year. This will ensure that there is sufficient capacity in the system to support all schools that wish to adopt the Teaching for Mastery approach, particularly those located in areas where need is greatest.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-01-16T17:24:38.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818730/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818730/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818730/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-08","Mathematics: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of schools in each NUTS 1 region have taken up the Teaching for Mastery Maths programmes; and what estimate she has made of the number of schools in each NUTS 1 region that will have taken up the programme by 2020.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","121494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818731","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-15","<p>This information could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-01-15T18:14:27.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818731/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818731/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818731/answer","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818731/answer/previousversion/33548","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-08","Refugees: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many applications for exceptional case funding for refugee family reunion applications under part 11 of the Immigration Rules have been (a) received and (b) accepted in each financial year since 1 April 2013.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","121495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818732","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-30","<p>The protection of children remains a priority for this Government and we keep this important area of the law under review.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport is currently developing proposals to extend the definition of a ‘position of trust’ in the Sexual Offences Act 2003, to bring into that definition sports coaches who hold a position of trust in relation to a child aged 16 or 17 under their care. We will consider these further with them once developed.</p><p> </p><p>Although I have not yet had any discussions with the Home Secretary on this matter directly, given my recent appointment.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-01-30T16:44:08.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818732/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818732/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818732/answer","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818732/answer/previousversion/33550","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-08","Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what discussions he has had with (a) the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport and (b) the Home Secretary on the extending the definition of a position of trust to include (i) sports coaches, (ii) youth leaders and (iii) religious leaders; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","121496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818733","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-16","<p>The information is not readily available, and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-01-16T17:30:33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818733/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818733/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818733/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-08","Social Security Benefits: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many tribunal hearings for appeals against the refusal of disability benefits have been attended by presenting officers; and how many of the original tribunal decisions were (a) upheld and (b) overturned since 1 April 2017.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","121497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818734","Department for Work and Pensions","true","2018-01-16","<p>While the Department has had presenting officers in the past, 2017 was the first time that individuals were recruited specifically into that role. Therefore there are no other specific recruitment to the presenting officer role in the years prior to 2017<del class="ministerial"> for ESA and PIP</del>.<ins class="ministerial">In 2017 DWP recruited 211 presenting officers.</ins></p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-01-16T17:39:32.073Z","2018-04-17T10:36:24.46Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818734/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818734/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818734/answer","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818734/answer/previousversion/34632","Biography information for Sarah Newton","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-08","Social Security Benefits: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many presenting officers have been recruited to represent his Department at tribunal appeals against the refusal of disability benefit in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","121498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818735","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-16","<p>Presenting officers use a wide range of guidance in their role that is not specifically aimed at them – for instance, guidance for decision makers which can be found in the Decision Makers Guide (DMG) and Advice for Decision Making Guide (ADM): <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/decision-makers-guide-staff-guide" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/decision-makers-guide-staff-guide</a>. This guidance is supplemented from time to time with updates to reflect legal and procedural changes.</p><p> </p><p>However, for your information I can direct you to generic guidance for presenting officers on the GOV.UK website. For Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) and Disability Living Allowance please refer to the DMG, paragraph 06429: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/658181/dmgch06.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/658181/dmgch06.pdf</a>; and for Personal Independence Payment and Universal Credit (including ‘new style’ ESA) please refer to the ADM, chapter A5429: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/661477/adma5.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/661477/adma5.pdf</a></p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-01-16T17:39:24.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818735/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818735/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818735/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-08","Social Security Benefits: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will place in the Library a copy of the written guidance issued to presenting officers for tribunal hearings of appeals against the refusal of (a) employment support allowance, (b) disability living allowance and (c) personal independence payments.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","121499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818736","Department for International Trade","false","2018-01-11","<p>The development of this economic research was an iterative process. The researchers provided regular progress updates in order for the Department to monitor delivery against the research specification.</p>","Beverley and Holderness","Graham Stuart",,"2018-01-11T16:53:06.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818736/answer","Biography information for Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818736/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818736/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-01-08","Trade Agreements: Arbitration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, when officials in his Department received a draft report of the research conducted by Copenhagen Economics and Van Bael & Bellis into the design of the UK Trade Remedies Framework.","false","Biography information for Gareth Snell","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Gareth Snell","121500"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818737","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-16","<p>There are no specific plans for tea bags.</p><p> </p><p>In December the Secretary of State chaired an industry roundtable on plastics and outlined a four point plan for tackling plastic waste that takes action at each stage of the product lifecycle – production, consumption and end of life: cutting the total amount of plastic in circulation; reducing the number of different plastics in use; improving the rate of recycling; supporting comprehensive recycling collections to make it easier for individuals to recycle.</p><p> </p><p>We set out further steps in our 25 Year Environment Plan, available here:</p><p> </p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/673203/25-year-environment-plan.pdf</p><p> </p><p>We will also be conducting a call for evidence this year, seeking views on how taxing and charging the most environmentally damaging single use plastics could help reduce waste.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","121503","2018-01-16T12:11:37.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818737/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818737/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818737/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-08","Tea: Polymers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether he plans to encourage food manufacturers to produce tea bags without the use of polymers.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","121501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818738","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-15","<p>I am committed to tackling all forms of leasehold abuse and promoting fairness and transparency for the growing number of leaseholders. On 21 December 2017, the Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government (formerly the Department for Communities and Local Government) published its response to the consultation on ‘Tackling unfair practices in the leasehold market’. (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/tackling-unfair-practices-in-the-leasehold-market" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/tackling-unfair-practices-in-the-leasehold-market</a>).</p><p>This set out a range of measures to crackdown on unfair leasehold practices, including introducing legislation to restrict ground rents for newly established long leases of houses and flats to a peppercorn (zero financial value). This will apply to new and non-new build properties.</p><p>A full impact assessment will be published ahead of legislation being brought forward.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","121504","2018-01-15T17:50:40.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818738/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818738/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818738/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2018-01-08","Ground Rent: Leasehold","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to tackle the issue of exploitative ground rent charges being levied on leaseholders of non-new build properties.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","121502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818739","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-16","<p>There are no specific plans for tea bags.</p><p> </p><p>In December the Secretary of State chaired an industry roundtable on plastics and outlined a four point plan for tackling plastic waste that takes action at each stage of the product lifecycle – production, consumption and end of life: cutting the total amount of plastic in circulation; reducing the number of different plastics in use; improving the rate of recycling; supporting comprehensive recycling collections to make it easier for individuals to recycle.</p><p> </p><p>We set out further steps in our 25 Year Environment Plan, available here:</p><p> </p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/673203/25-year-environment-plan.pdf</p><p> </p><p>We will also be conducting a call for evidence this year, seeking views on how taxing and charging the most environmentally damaging single use plastics could help reduce waste.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","121501","2018-01-16T12:11:37.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818739/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818739/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818739/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-08","Tea: Polymers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to reduce the quantity of plastic polymers used in the production of tea bags.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","121503"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818740","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-15","<p>I am committed to tackling all forms of leasehold abuse and promoting fairness and transparency for the growing number of leaseholders. On 21 December 2017, the Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government (formerly the Department for Communities and Local Government) published its response to the consultation on ‘Tackling unfair practices in the leasehold market’. (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/tackling-unfair-practices-in-the-leasehold-market" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/tackling-unfair-practices-in-the-leasehold-market</a>).</p><p>This set out a range of measures to crackdown on unfair leasehold practices, including introducing legislation to restrict ground rents for newly established long leases of houses and flats to a peppercorn (zero financial value). This will apply to new and non-new build properties.</p><p>A full impact assessment will be published ahead of legislation being brought forward.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","121502","2018-01-15T17:50:40.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818740/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818740/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818740/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2018-01-08","Ground Rent: Leasehold","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of extending the roll-out of the ban on ground rent for new build homes to leaseholders of non-new build properties.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","121504"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818741","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-11","<p>Disclosure of any fruitless payments made in 2017-18 will be made in accordance with the requirements set out in Managing Public Money and published in the Department’s 2017/18 Annual Report and Accounts, planned for July 2018. The Department waits until its Annual Accounts to publish this information so that the National Audit Office can verify to the House that any disclosures made meet audit standards.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-01-11T14:59:29.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818741/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818741/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818741/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-08","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, which fruitless payments in excess of £30,000 her Department has made by (a) recipient of each such payment, (b) purpose of each such payment, (c) value of each such payment and (d) reason that payment was classified as fruitless in the 2017-18 financial year to date.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","121505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818742","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-11","<p>No fruitless payments in excess of £30,000 have been made this year.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2018-01-11T17:46:45.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818742/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818742/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818742/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2018-01-08","Department for Communities and Local Government: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, which fruitless payments in excess of £30,000 his Department has made by (a) recipient of each such payment, (b) purpose of each such payment, (c) value of each such payment and (d) reason that payment was classified as fruitless in the 2017-18 financial year to date.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","121506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818743","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-11","<p>Figures for 2017-18 will be available once the DCMS Annual Report and Accounts are audited by the National Audit Office, and laid before Parliament.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-01-11T13:44:55.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818743/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818743/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818743/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-08","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, which fruitless payments in excess of £30,000 her Department has made by (a) recipient of each such payment, (b) purpose of each such payment, (c) value of each such payment and (d) reason that payment was classified as fruitless in the 2017-18 financial year to date.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","121507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818744","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-16","<p>The department did not make any fruitless payments in excess of £30,000 between 1 April 2017 and 9 January 2018.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong><br> </strong></p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-01-16T12:18:54.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818744/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818744/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818744/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-08","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, which fruitless payments in excess of £30,000 her Department has made by (a) recipient of each such payment, (b) purpose of each such payment, (c) value of each such payment and (d) reason that payment was classified as fruitless in the 2017-18 financial year to date.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","121508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818745","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-11","<p>The final Accessibility Action Plan will set out the Government’s updated plans for making transport more inclusive so that disabled people can travel more confidently.</p><p>The Department is aware that transport to hospital appointments is an area of particular concern to many disabled people, and the Department plans to write to the Department of Health and Social Care on this matter shortly.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-01-11T14:50:14.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818745/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818745/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818745/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-08","Patients: Travel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 21 December 2017 to Question 119952, whether the Government revised Accessibility Action Plan will make specific reference to the issues that face disabled people while attending hospital appointments.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","121509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818746","Cabinet Office","false","2018-01-11","<p>The Prime Minister has stated that the United Kingdom will cease to be a member of the European Union on 29 March 2019, at the conclusion of the Article 50 process. There are currently no plans for any ceremonial or official events to mark the formal exit of the UK from the EU, although the Cabinet Office and the Department for Exiting the European Union will keep this under review.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2018-01-11T11:11:14.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818746/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818746/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818746/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-08","Brexit: Festivals and Special Occasions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Government is planning any ceremonial or official events to mark the formal exit of the UK from the EU.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","121510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818747","Attorney General","false","2018-01-15","<p>According to our records, in 2009 the Attorney General’s Office received requests to refer John Worboys’s sentence to the Court of Appeal from a charity that campaigned against violence against women, and from an MP who passed on a constituent’s complaint about the sentence.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2018-01-15T16:57:07.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818747/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818747/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818747/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2018-01-08","John Worboys","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many requests were received by his Department requesting the referral of the sentence in R v John Worboys to the Court of Appeal under the Unduly Lenient Sentence Scheme in 2009; and who those requests were made by.","false","Biography information for Gareth Johnson","Dartford","Gareth Johnson","121511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818748","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-11","<p>Government support for small and medium sized enterprises, including suppliers to Nissan, is provided through a range of measures and funding competitions which make the UK one of the best locations to locate and grow an automotive business. This includes the Advanced Manufacturing Supply Chain Initiative, with projects running through to 2019, and the £1bn Advanced Propulsion Centre, which promotes collaborative R&amp;D between suppliers and vehicle makers to develop products to improve efficiency and reduce emissions.</p><p>Furthermore, and as part of a programme of long term investment in the North East, the North East LEP Growth Deal, announced on 23 January 2017, was awarded £49.7m. Through the North East LEP Growth Deal we are supporting jobs growth and economic development with £379.6m of Local Growth Fund. This includes £42m of funding for the international Advanced Manufacturing Park, which will provide a world class environment for high tech advanced industries and advanced manufacturing businesses, including the automotive sector. Since its launch in 2016, the North East Growth Hub has engaged with over 7300 businesses, delivered 117 intensive assists and helped 728 individuals to start a business.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-01-11T15:14:13.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818748/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818748/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818748/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-08","Manufacturing Industries: Easington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if the Government will provide incentives to (a) businesses and (b) the automotive industry to locate manufacturing facilities in the Easington constituency.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","121512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818749","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-11","<p>There are no plans to use post code enumerators to determine the eligibility of Winter Fuel Payments for those living in other member states for the reasons set out in the explanatory memorandum to The Social Fund Winter Fuel Payment (Amendment) Regulations 2014/3270, details of which can be found in the link below.</p><p><a href="https://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2014/3270/memorandum/contents" target="_blank">https://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2014/3270/memorandum/contents</a></p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2018-01-11T16:46:21.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818749/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818749/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818749/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-08","Winter Fuel Payments: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will recalculate winter fuel payments for eligible claimants living in other EU member states using postcode enumerators to devise a more accurate system than measuring the national average of temperatures in each such country.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","121513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818750","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-16","<p>While the government has not made a specific assessment of the impact on rates of liver disease, the new duty band is expected to have a positive impact on the health of individuals in the UK.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2018-01-16T16:21:25.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818750/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818750/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818750/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-08","Cider: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the new duty band for high strength white cider on rates of liver disease.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","121514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818751","Home Office","false","2018-01-15","<p>The Modern Slavery helpline is funded by the private sector. The Home Office had no involvement in any aspect of the tender for the helpline, including the process through which funding was awarded. The tender was carried out by Polaris, a US-based NGO. Polaris runs a similar helpline in the US. There is no inquiry into the awarding of this contract.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins","121519","2018-01-15T12:36:51.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818751/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818751/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818751/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-08","Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will publish the terms of reference for the inquiry into the awarding of a contract for the national modern slavery helpline.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","121515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818752","Department of Health","false","2018-01-16","<p>The information requested is not collected centrally.</p><p>The provision of patient transport services is a matter for local National Health Service commissioners. NHS England has advised that High Weald Havens Clinical Commissioning Group commissioned an independent investigation into these events, which reported in March 2017. Accordingly, there are no plans to undertake a further independent investigation.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","121517 ; 121520","2018-01-16T16:19:44.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818752/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818752/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818752/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2018-01-08","Coperforma","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what information his Department holds on how much was paid by NHS bodies to cover private sector liabilities to workers as a result of the performance problems with Patient Transport Services provided by Coperforma; how much money has been recovered to the public purse from Coperforma as a result of those performance problems; whether outstanding liabilities relating to that Coperforma contract will be recovered following the liquidation of Coperforma Ltd; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","121516"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818753","Department of Health","false","2018-01-16","<p>The information requested is not collected centrally.</p><p>The provision of patient transport services is a matter for local National Health Service commissioners. NHS England has advised that High Weald Havens Clinical Commissioning Group commissioned an independent investigation into these events, which reported in March 2017. Accordingly, there are no plans to undertake a further independent investigation.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","121516 ; 121520","2018-01-16T16:19:44.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818753/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818753/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818753/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2018-01-08","Coperforma","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will commission a formal, independent investigation into the outsourcing and performance problems of the Patient Transport Services provided by Coperforma and arms length driver operatives, including an assessment of monies paid to Coperforma and monies paid by the public sector as a result of Coperforma's performance failures; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","121517"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818754","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-11","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions has answered 19 written parliamentary questions explaining that the requested information was not available on the grounds of it not being collected or held centrally, out of a total of 1986 parliamentary questions that have been answered. This figure includes some that were partially answered.</p><p> </p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-01-11T11:27:10.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818754/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818754/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/818754/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-08","Department for Work and Pensions: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pension, how many and what proportion of his Department's Answers to Written Parliamentary Questions in the 2017-18 Session to date have referred to the information requested not being (a) collected or (b) collated centrally.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","121518"
